ðŸ”‘ Core Networking Concepts - Detailed

1. IP Address - Ghar ka Pata

.........Check your IP address..........
ip a            ------------->             All network interfaces
hostname -I     ------------->             Only IP addresses
ifconfig       -------------->             Old command (deprecated)

--->   Output Example:
--->   enp0s3: <BROADCAST,MULTICAST,UP,LOWER_UP> mtu 1500
--->   inet 192.168.1.100/24 brd 192.168.1.255 scope global dynamic noprefixroute enp0s3


Key Points:

-> IPv4: 192.168.1.100 (32-bit, most common)

-> IPv6: 2001:0db8:85a3:0000:0000:8a2e:0370:7334 (128-bit, future)

-> CIDR Notation: /24 means subnet mask 255.255.255.0

-> Private IP Ranges:

--------> 10.0.0.0 - 10.255.255.255 (Large companies)

--------> 172.16.0.0 - 172.31.255.255 (Medium networks)

--------> 192.168.0.0 - 192.168.255.255 (Home/Office)


2. Subnet - Society/Colony

# Check network route
ip route show
route -n

-> Output:
-> default via 192.168.1.1 dev enp0s3 proto dhcp metric 100
-> 192.168.1.0/24 dev enp0s3 proto kernel scope link src 192.168.1.100 metric 100


Subnetting Example:

IP: 192.168.1.100/24
Network: 192.168.1.0
Broadcast: 192.168.1.255
Usable IPs: 192.168.1.1 to 192.168.1.254
Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0


3. Gateway - Society ka Main Gate

-> Gateway = Router = Default route to internet

-> Usually: 192.168.1.1 or 10.0.0.1

# Find gateway
ip route | grep default


4. DNS - Phonebook

->  Check DNS servers
    cat /etc/resolv.conf

->  DNS testing commands
    nslookup google.com
    dig google.com                # More detailed
    host google.com

-> Output:
-> Server:         8.8.8.8
-> Address:        8.8.8.8#53
-> Non-authoritative answer:
-> Name:   google.com
-> Address: 142.250.182.46

Popular DNS Servers:

-->  Google: 8.8.8.8, 8.8.4.4

-->  Cloudflare: 1.1.1.1, 1.0.0.1

-->  OpenDNS: 208.67.222.222


ðŸšª Ports & Services - Ghar ke Rooms

Common Ports Every DevOps Engineer Should Know

--->  Check listening ports

sudo ss -tulnp                # Modern (recommended)
sudo netstat -tulnp           # Old but works

->  Output columns:
->  State      Recv-Q Send-Q Local Address:Port  Peer Address:Port
->  LISTEN     0      128    0.0.0.0:22          0.0.0.0:*       users:(("sshd",pid=123,fd=3))


Essential Ports Table

Port	         Service	         Protocol	           Use in DevOps
22	           SSH	             TCP	               Server management, Git operations
80	           HTTP	             TCP	               Web traffic (unencrypted)
443          	 HTTPS	           TCP	               Secure web traffic
53	           DNS	             UDP/TCP	           Domain name resolution
3306	         MySQL	           TCP	               Database connections
5432	         PostgreSQL	       TCP	               Database connections
27017	         MongoDB	         TCP	               NoSQL database
8080	         Jenkins/Tomcat	   TCP	               CI/CD tools, Java apps
9000	         Portainer	       TCP	               Docker management
3000	         Node.js	         TCP	               Development servers
6379	         Redis	           TCP	               Caching service


ðŸ” SSH (Secure Shell) - DevOps ka Best Friend

SSH Key Generation & Management

-> Generate SSH key pair
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"

-> -t: Type (rsa, ed25519)
-> -b: Bits (4096 recommended)
-> -C: Comment (usually email)

--> Files created:

->>   ~/.ssh/id_rsa      â†’ Private key (NEVER SHARE!)
->>   ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub  â†’ Public key (share with servers/GitHub)

--> Check key fingerprint
   ssh-keygen -l -f ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub

-->  Copy public key to server (password-less login)
     ssh-copy-id username@server_ip


------- >>> SSH Config File (Time Saver!)

->  Create/edit SSH config
    nano ~/.ssh/config

->  Add:
Host myserver
    HostName 192.168.1.100
    User ubuntu
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_rsa
    Port 22

# Now connect with just:
ssh myserver


SSH Tunnel (Port Forwarding)

-->  Local port forwarding

ssh -L 8080:localhost:80 user@server

--> Browser me localhost:8080 open karo â†’ server ka port 80 dikhega

--> Remote port forwarding

ssh -R 3000:localhost:8080 user@server

--> Server pe port 3000 â†’ your local 8080 connect hoga


ðŸŒ Internet Testing & Troubleshooting

  Connectivity Testing Commands

---> Basic ping
ping -c 4 google.com          # 4 packets bhejo
ping -i 2 8.8.8.8             # Every 2 seconds

---> Trace route (packet ka rasta dekho)
traceroute google.com
mtr google.com                # Real-time traceroute

---> Network speed test
speedtest-cli                 # Install: sudo apt install speedtest-cli

---> Check MTU (Maximum Transmission Unit)
ping -s 1472 -M do 8.8.8.8    # Fragment avoidance test


HTTP/Web Testing  ------------->>>>>

->   Download/Test web pages
curl https://google.com                # HTML fetch
curl -I https://google.com             # Only headers
curl -v https://google.com             # Verbose (full details)

->   Download files
wget https://example.com/file.zip
wget -O customname.zip https://example.com/file.zip

->   API Testing (DevOps me bahut use)
curl -X GET "https://api.github.com/users/octocat"
curl -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"name":"test"}' https://api.example.com


ðŸ”¥ Firewall & Security (UFW - Uncomplicated Firewall)
--->Basic Firewall Setup

---> Check status
sudo ufw status
sudo ufw status numbered      # Rule numbers ke sath

---> Enable/Disable
sudo ufw enable
sudo ufw disable

---> Default policies
sudo ufw default deny incoming   # Sab block karo
sudo ufw default allow outgoing  # Sab allow karo

---> Allow specific ports
sudo ufw allow 22/tcp           # SSH
sudo ufw allow 80/tcp           # HTTP
sudo ufw allow 443/tcp          # HTTPS
sudo ufw allow 9090/tcp         # Custom port

---> Allow from specific IP
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.50 to any port 22

---> Delete rule
sudo ufw delete allow 80
sudo ufw delete 3              # Rule number 3 delete karo


--------------->>>>  Advanced Firewall Rules

---->> Rate limiting (DDoS protection)
       sudo ufw limit 22/tcp

---->> Allow port range
       sudo ufw allow 8000:9000/tcp

---->> Deny specific IP
       sudo ufw deny from 203.0.113.4

----->>> Application profiles
sudo ufw app list              # Available apps
sudo ufw allow 'Nginx Full'    # Predefined profile


-------->>> ðŸ”§ Network Configuration Files
1. Network Interfaces (/etc/netplan/)

yaml -----------

-> Ubuntu 18.04+ (Netplan)
sudo nano /etc/netplan/01-netcfg.yaml

network:
  version: 2
  ethernets:
    eth0:
      dhcp4: no
      addresses:
        - 192.168.1.100/24
      gateway4: 192.168.1.1
      nameservers:
        addresses: [8.8.8.8, 1.1.1.1]

-> Apply changes
sudo netplan apply

2. Hosts File (/etc/hosts)
-------bash 

---> Local DNS override
sudo nano /etc/hosts

---> Add:
127.0.0.1   localhost
192.168.1.100  server1.local dev-server
192.168.1.101  database.local

---> Test
ping server1.local


3. Resolv.conf (/etc/resolv.conf)  [bash]

# DNS configuration
sudo nano /etc/resolv.conf

# Add:
nameserver 8.8.8.8
nameserver 1.1.1.1
options timeout:2 attempts:3


ðŸ§ª Practical Lab Exercises  ---------
------->> Exercise 1: Network Discovery  [bash]

# 1. Find your IP and subnet
ip a | grep inet
ip route

# 2. Find gateway
ip route | grep default

# 3. Trace path to Google
traceroute google.com

# 4. Check open ports on your system
sudo ss -tulnp | grep LISTEN


Exercise 2: SSH Setup  [ bash ]

# 1. Generate SSH key
ssh-keygen -t ed25519

# 2. View public key
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

# 3. Setup GitHub SSH
# GitHub â†’ Settings â†’ SSH Keys â†’ Add new
# Paste your public key

# 4. Test connection
ssh -T git@github.com
# Should show: "Hi username! You've successfully authenticated..."


------------>>>>>>>>>>>Exercise 3: Firewall Configuration    [ bash ]

# 1. Reset firewall
sudo ufw --force reset

# 2. Set defaults
sudo ufw default deny incoming
sudo ufw default allow outgoing

# 3. Allow essential services
sudo ufw allow 22/tcp comment 'SSH'
sudo ufw allow 80/tcp comment 'HTTP'
sudo ufw allow 443/tcp comment 'HTTPS'

# 4. Enable and check
sudo ufw enable
sudo ufw status verbose



ðŸ“Š Network Troubleshooting Checklist

------>>>> When something doesn't work:

1.  Ping gateway: ping 192.168.1.1

2.  Ping external IP: ping 8.8.8.8

3.  Ping domain: ping google.com

  -> If #1 fails â†’ Local network issue

  -> If #2 fails â†’ Internet issue

  -> If #3 fails â†’ DNS issue

4.  Check DNS: nslookup google.com

5.  Check ports: sudo ss -tulnp

6.  Check firewall: sudo ufw status

7.  Check routes: ip route


